					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/mlister" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3027978); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=3027978&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227467" alt="mlister" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=3027978)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/mlister" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(3027978); return false;" >mlister</a></span> <span class="odate time_1524277161 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">21 Apr 2018 02:19</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3775744">
									

<p>I want to like this, but I'm in solid novote territory.</p>
<p>There's a couple of golden lines in here, but the quality of the writing bridging them feels inadequate. At times it feels like those lines were written first, and the rest is just there to justify their existence. There are also a few lines that feel like they were meant to be heavier than they were supposed to be, which is slightly jarring.</p>
<p>Besides that, it's hard to be emotionally invested. Our two anchor characters face a decent chunk of development off-screen, haphazardly move in and out of focus, and die mildly unceremonious deaths. I've also got to agree with Soulless on the vignettes.</p>
<p>I do like what the article is going for, but the structure and shifting focus do more to hurt it than to help, in my opinion.</p>

							</div>

										<div class="signature">
					<hr class="signature-separator"/>
					

<p>No signature defined.</p>

